-- Japan, South Korea, China, India, Thailand: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-11-15T22:45:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-15/japan-south-korea-china-india-thailand-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  Masamitsu Sakurai, head of the Japan Association of
Corporate Executives, will hold a media briefing at 1:30 p.m.  The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. its report on
Japan’s demand for services in September. The nation’s tertiary
index, which captures 63 percent of the economy, fell 0.5
percent in September from August, when it slid 0.2 percent,
according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was 1.05 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.12 per dollar at 7:41 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea: Six of 13 economists surveyed by Bloomberg say
the Bank of Korea will raise its benchmark interest rate by 25
basis points to 2.50 percent. The decision will be announced at
10 a.m. local time.  The yield on the 3.75 percent debt due June 2013 was 3.48
percent. The won was at 1,131.81 per dollar.  China: The National Bureau of Statistics will say foreign
direct investment rose 10.4 percent in October, the most since
July, according to a Bloomberg survey. Investment climbed 6.1
percent in the previous month.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 3.65
percent. The yuan was at 6.6455 per dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell 65 billion baht
($2.2 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills and 50 billion baht
of three-year bonds.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.70
percent. The baht was at 29.92 per dollar.  India: India will sell 60 billion rupees ($1.3 billion) of
91- and 364-day bills. The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May
2020 was 8.07 percent. The rupee was at 45.11 per dollar.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at   fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net . 